body:
**Description**: Fix the nuget build break caused by change #4718 

**Motivation and Context**

- The fix is to rename the "session_options_config_keys.h" to "onnxruntime_session_options_config_keys.h" 

Pending Nuget GPU pipeline run, https://aiinfra.visualstudio.com/Lotus/_build/results?buildId=130821&view=results
Will not merge unless the pipeline pass on the branch

title: Initial changes to disable code in a minimal build
body:
**Description**: 
Initial set of changes to disable code in the minimal build. 
Breaking changes into multiple PRs so they're more easily reviewed so this set of changes adds the infrastructure to disable the majority of the code to exclude.
Needs to be integrated with de/serialization code before being testable so changes are all off by default.

Changes are limited to
  - adding ability to #ifdef out code from a minimal build
  - moving some things around so there are fewer #ifdef statements
    - also moved some things in InferenceSession.h so there's only one 'protected:' and one 'private:' section
  - moving definition of some one-line methods into the header so we don't need to #ifdef out in a .cc as well
  - cmake updates to exclude things
    - also added separate flag for a build that just has reduced op support

**Motivation and Context**
Infrastructure for a minimal build.

title: enable nuget packaging in local builds
body:
**Description**: This PR enables creating nuget packages in local builds (on windows and linux) for cpu, cuda, tensorrt, dnnl and openvino execution providers.

Adding a new build option --build_nuget which will trigger csharp builds + nuget package creation + csharp test (when tests are enabled) at the end of the build process. 
Example:
build.bat --build_nuget --config Debug|Release|etc
creates 2 nuget packages (Managed and Native) and copies them to "NativeBuildOutputDir\nuget-artifacts"

**Motivation and Context**
- There is a partner ask to be able to build openvino packages on ubuntu
- Currently nuget building on linux is a 2 steps process where 2nd step involves jumping on a windows box for nuget creation.

title: Mixed Precision Transformer and Gradient Builder Refactor
body:
Rebase previous PR on Cheng's changes. This PR includes:
- Refactor the mixed precision transformer to support other mixed precision data types other than FP16, only FP16 needs loss scale.
- Move mixed precision transformer before gradient builder, i.e., transform mixed precision on forward graph only.
- Add supporting mixed precision data types such as FP16/BFloat16 to gradient builder.
- Change Adam/Lamb optimizer to support more mixed precision data types other than FP16.

This PR is a preparation to support BFloat16 training. The target is to refactor the mixed precision transformer and gradient builder and make sure current FP32 and FP16 training works as usual. So it does NOT include any frontend parameter change or CUDA change to support new mixed precision data type (BFloat16).

Pref test result on Dev3:

Max bs=66
Throughput: 190.402 (Adam)
Throughput: 183.76 (Lamb)

FP16, seq=512
Max bs=10
Throughput: 37.5534 (Adam)
Throughput: 36.1645 (Lamb)

title: MatMul Gradient optimization for dB when B's is 2D tensor
body:
**Description**: 
Y = MatMul(A, B)
In general form: dB = ReduceSum(A' * dY) 
For example A[500, 4, 1024], B[1024, 1024], Y[500, 4, 1024]. 
Pre-ReduceSum Tensor = A' * dY => [500, 1024, 1024], which could be very large (2GB in fp32). 
However, this temporary tensor is immediately latter reduced-sum into [1024, 1024]. 
This fix is meant to avoid generating the large intermediate tensor. 

This is achieved by reshaping A and dY into 2D tensors first, A => [500x4, 1024], dY => [500x4, 1024] and dB can be obtained without ReduceSum and intermediate tensor. 

However, similar trick **cannot** be applied for dA calculation. 
For example, A[1024, 1024], B[500, 1024, 4], Y[500, 1024, 4]. 
dA = ReduceSum(dY * B')
The collapsing dimensions (500 and 4) for dY and B are not adjacent to each other, so a simple Reshape is not working here. 
If we encounter such case in the future, we will need another fix.

title: Enable rejecting models based on onnx opset
body:
**Description**: 
This PR adds the ability to reject models which import unreleased onnx opsets. 

- By default unreleased opsets are rejected however someone who wants to specifically use the unreleased opset (for development or experimentation) should be able to do it by setting environment variable ALLOW_RELEASED_ONNX_OPSET_ONLY to 0. 

- CIs pipelines for CPU and GPU providers (inference and training on all platforms ) also allow unreleased opsets to allow testing the changes.

- Release pipelines do not allow unreleased opsets and any tests targeting ops from unreleased opsets will be skipped.

**Motivation and Context**
- ORT has decided to use commits from onnx master branch as well (instead of release branch only). This change is intended to speed up development process but we still need to make sure in released packages users dont take any dependency on "in development" onnx opsets which are subject to change.

title: Put operators in-between Wait and Record
body:
This PR changes computation pattern from
```
Wait -> Recv -> Wait -> FW -> Record -> Send -> Record ->
Wait -> Recv -> Wait -> BW -> Record -> Send -> Record
```
to
```
Wait -> Recv -> **Record** -> Wait -> FW -> Record -> **Wait** -> Send -> Record ->
Wait -> Recv -> **Record** -> Wait -> BW -> Record -> **Wait** -> Send -> Record
```

This allows us to separately control when Recv, Send, FW, and BW to happen.

title: ORT DirectML EP for Iron release, ONNX 1.5
body:
**Description**: This includes collected changes for this release.

-	7 operators for ONNX 1.7 (opset 12):
o	Celu-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2575) (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2573)
o	GreaterOrEqual-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2606)
o	LessOrEqual-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2606)
o	ArgMax-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2461) - add "select_last_index" parameter for value ties.
o	ArgMin-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2461) - add "select_last_index" parameter for value ties.
o	GatherND-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2585) - add `batch_dim` parameter.
o	RoiAlign-10 (https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06870)
-	New data types were added to existing operators:
o	Clip-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2532) - add integer type
o	Max-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2608) - add integer type
o	Min-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2608) - add integer type
o	MaxPool-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2510) - add int8 type
o	ReduceMax-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2516) - add int8 type
o	ReduceMin-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2516) - add int8 type
o	Pow-12 (https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2666) - allow exponent to be int (can differ from base type)
-	Higher dimension support 1D to 8D added to these operators:
o	ElementWise*
o	Activation*
o	Reduce*
o	ArgMin/ArgMax
o	Gather*
o	Scatter*
o	OneHot
-	64-bit support for indices on GPU's that support it (Gather, Scatter, OneHot, ArgMax/ArgMin, Cast).

**Motivation and Context**
- _Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?_
This updates the DML EP for ONNX opset 12 support on the GPU.

title: Fuse softmax(a + b) in case of simple broadcast
body:
**Description**: Fuse softmax(a + b) in case of simple broadcasting. The target fusion is softmax(scores + mask) used during attention mechanism. In this case mask elements are either 0 or -10,000. It is of shape [batch_size, sequence_length]. The mask is broadcast to attention scores of shape [batch_size, num_heads, sequence_length, sequence_length]. This fusion is applied after the training graph is constructed. 

Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
For phase 2 Nvidia BERT training I observe 1.8% performance benefit if turned ON.

Another PR will address fusing softmax_grad( dropout_grad(...) ) for an expected similar benefit.

title: Place shape related compute nodes in CPU
body:
For non-CPU EPs, there are subgraphs sandwiched by CPUOutputs and CPUInputs, such as the examples shown below. They are commonly shape related subgraph that first reads-in a shape, manipulates it, and reshape it back to some other shape. It's better to place such subgraphs in CPU, to avoid the memcpy back and forth between Host and Device. 

Example 1:  Circled sub-graph should be placed in CPU
